instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The framework defines a Digital‑Twin lifecycle that begins with Building Control Engineers enriching BIM models on which devices (sensors, actuators, controllers) and control logic are defined. Enriched BIM models are processed by a Model‑Driven Engineering (MDE) pipeline that extracts a semantic representation and automatically generates deployable Digital‑Twin artifacts (configuration bundles, runtime services) with minimal manual intervention. These artifacts are deployed into a runtime environment where the twin is synchronized with the physical building via real‑time data exchange. The framework’s modular architecture provides standardized extension points that allow DT Engineers to attach custom services, thereby enabling iterative evolution of the twin. Each lifecycle stage is clearly separated—modeling, transformation, deployment, runtime operation—to support governance and traceability."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model validity is ensured by Eclipse Ditto’s policy‑based validation, which enforces sensor data ranges, units, and pre‑execution checks on actuator commands. Fault tolerance and data integrity are achieved through Hono’s at‑least‑once message delivery and Ditto’s persistent event storage, preserving message history across network failures. Validation processes include automatic checks during the conversion phase of enriched BIM models and runtime verification against defined policies, providing continuous assurance of data quality and model consistency."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The framework aligns with AECO‑centric BIM standards (Revit/IFC‑based BIM) for device and control logic definition. It adopts open telemetry standards for real‑time data exchange and leverages recognized open‑source Digital‑Twin platforms such as Eclipse Ditto and BaSyx to provide connectivity and standard compliance, thereby ensuring interoperability across heterogeneous building assets."
]
